<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="127" name="Amines">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Amines are derivatives of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ammonia (NH3)</option><option id="B">Water</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by replacement of H by alkyl/aryl groups.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of one H in NH3 by R group gives ____ amine.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°)</option><option id="B">Secondary (2°)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-NH2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of two H in NH3 by R groups gives ____ amine.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary (2°)</option><option id="B">Tertiary (3°)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R2NH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of all three H in NH3 by R groups gives ____ amine.</text>
            <option id="A">Tertiary (3°)</option><option id="B">Quaternary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R3N.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Geometry of ammonia and amines is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pyramidal</option><option id="B">Planar</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Nitrogen is sp3 hybridized with one lone pair.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for Methanamine is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Methylamine</option><option id="B">Ethylamine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simplest aliphatic amine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>IUPAC name of Aniline is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzenamine</option><option id="B">Phenylamine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Both names are accepted by IUPAC.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Arylamines have -NH2 group directly attached to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzene ring</option><option id="B">Aliphatic chain</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Aniline.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of Nitro compounds with Fe/HCl gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary amines</option><option id="B">Amides</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard method for aniline preparation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ammonolysis of alkyl halides is a ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleophilic substitution</option><option id="B">Electrophilic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NH3 acts as nucleophile.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ammonolysis of RX usually gives a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mixture of 1°, 2°, 3° and quaternary salts</option><option id="B">Pure primary amine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Disadvantage of this method.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of Nitriles with LiAlH4 gives ____ amines.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°)</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-CN -&gt; R-CH2NH2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of Amides with LiAlH4 gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amines with same number of carbons</option><option id="B">Amines with one less carbon</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-CONH2 -&gt; R-CH2NH2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gabriel Phthalimide synthesis is used to prepare ____ amines.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary aliphatic amines only</option><option id="B">Aromatic amines</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aryl halides don't undergo nucleophilic substitution with phthalimide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hoffmann Bromamide degradation converts amide to amine with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">One less carbon atom</option><option id="B">One more carbon</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses Br2 and NaOH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lower aliphatic amines are ____ at room temperature.</text>
            <option id="A">Gases with fishy odor</option><option id="B">Liquids</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Methylamine, Ethylamine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling points: 1° &gt; 2° &gt; 3° amines (isomeric). Correct? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to decreasing extent of intermolecular H-bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amines are ____ in nature due to lone pair on Nitrogen.</text>
            <option id="A">Basic</option><option id="B">Acidic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Act as Lewis bases or Bronsted bases.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basic strength: Aliphatic amines are ____ basic than ammonia.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to +I effect of alkyl groups.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basic strength: Aromatic amines are ____ basic than ammonia.</text>
            <option id="A">Less</option><option id="B">More</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lone pair is delocalized into the benzene ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Order of basicity for methyl amines in aqueous solution is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(CH3)2NH &gt; CH3NH2 &gt; (CH3)3N &gt; NH3</option><option id="B">3° &gt; 2° &gt; 1°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Combined effect of +I, solvation and steric factors.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acylation of amines involves reaction with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acid chlorides or anhydrides</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms amides.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbylamine reaction is given only by ____ amines.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°) Aliphatic/Aromatic</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produces foul smelling isocyanides.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of 1° amines with nitrous acid (HNO2) yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alcohols (aliphatic) or Diazonium salts (aromatic)</option><option id="B">Nitro compounds</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Release of Nitrogen gas is diagnostic for aliphatic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hinsberg's reagent is chemically ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzenesulphonyl chloride</option><option id="B">p-Toluenesulphonyl chloride</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to distinguish 1°, 2°, 3° amines.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hinsberg test: 1° amine gives a product that is ____ in alkali.</text>
            <option id="A">Soluble</option><option id="B">Insoluble</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to presence of acidic H in sulphonamide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hinsberg test: 2° amine gives a product that is ____ in alkali.</text>
            <option id="A">Insoluble</option><option id="B">Soluble</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No acidic hydrogen present.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hinsberg test: 3° amines ____ with reagent.</text>
            <option id="A">Do not react</option><option id="B">React immediately</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lack of replaceable H on Nitrogen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bromination of Aniline with Br2/H2O gives ____ product.</text>
            <option id="A">2,4,6-tribromoaniline (White ppt)</option><option id="B">o/p-bromoaniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly activated ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Direct nitration of Aniline gives signficant amount of meta product. Why?</text>
            <option id="A">In acid, aniline forms anilinium ion (meta directing)</option><option id="B">-NH2 is meta directing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formation of -NH3+ ion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sulphonation of aniline gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sulphanilic acid (as Zwitterion)</option><option id="B">Aniline nitrate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dipolar ion structure (+NH3-C6H4-SO3-).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aniline does NOT undergo ____ alkylation.</text>
            <option id="A">Friedel-Crafts</option><option id="B">Wurtz</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>AlCl3 catalyst bonds with lone pair of N, deactivating the ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diazonium salts have general formula ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ar-N2+ X-</option><option id="B">R-NH2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Important synthetic intermediates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Benzene diazonium chloride is stable only at ____ temperatures.</text>
            <option id="A">0 - 5 °C (Low temp)</option><option id="B">Room temp</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Decomposes above 5°C.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sandmeyer reaction: ArN2+ + CuCl/HCl -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chlorobenzene (ArCl)</option><option id="B">Aniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Replacement of diazonium group by Cl.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gattermann reaction: ArN2+ + Cu/HCl -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chlorobenzene</option><option id="B">Aniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Modified Sandmeyer using copper powder.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Balz-Schiemann reaction is used to prepare ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fluorobenzene</option><option id="B">Iodobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heating fluoroborate salt of diazonium.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coupling reaction: Benzenediazonium chloride + Phenol -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-Hydroxyazobenzene (Orange dye)</option><option id="B">Aniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Azo coupling in basic medium.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coupling reaction: Benzenediazonium chloride + Aniline -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-Aminoazobenzene (Yellow dye)</option><option id="B">Phenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Azo coupling in acidic medium.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Importance of diazonium salts: They allow introduction of ____ groups.</text>
            <option id="A">-Cl, -Br, -I, -CN, -OH, -F, -H etc.</option><option id="B">Only -NH2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly versatile for aromatic synthesis.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Basicity order of amines in gas phase: 3° &gt; 2° &gt; 1° &gt; NH3. Correct? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based solely on +I effect of alkyl groups.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basicity order of ethyl amines in aqueous solution: 2° &gt; 3° &gt; 1°? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes ((C2H5)2NH &gt; (C2H5)3N &gt; C2H5NH2 &gt; NH3)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Steric effect dominates for bulky ethyl groups in 3°.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aniline + Acetyl chloride (CH3COCl) -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetanilide</option><option id="B">N-methylaniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard acylation for protecting -NH2 group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Why protect -NH2 in aniline before nitration?</text>
            <option id="A">To prevent oxidation and formation of unwanted products</option><option id="B">To make it meta directing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reduces reactivity and prevents anilinium formation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Preparation of p-nitroaniline from aniline requires ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetylation -&gt; Nitration -&gt; Hydrolysis</option><option id="B">Direct nitration</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific sequence to minimize o-isomer and meta-isomer.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Distinguish 1° and 2° amines by ____ test.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbylamine / Hinsberg</option><option id="B">Tollen's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1° reacts with CHCl3/KOH, 2° doesn't.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Libermann's Nitroso test is used for ____ amines.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary (2°)</option><option id="B">Primary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gives yellow oily nitrosoamine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mustard oil reaction: 1° amine + CS2 + HgCl2 -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkyl isothiocyanate (RNCS)</option><option id="B">Alkyl cyanide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic smell of mustard oil.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mendius reaction involves reduction of ____ using Na/ethanol.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkyl cyanides</option><option id="B">Nitroalkanes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Yields primary amines.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Curtius rearrangement: Acyl azide (RCON3) -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary amine</option><option id="B">Amide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Thermal decomposition followed by hydrolysis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lossen rearrangement of hydroxamic acids yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary amines</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar to Hoffmann/Curtius.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Schmidt reaction of carboxylic acids with hydrazoic acid yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary amines with one less carbon</option><option id="B">Amides</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>RCOOH + N3H -&gt; RNH2 + CO2 + N2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tertiary amines do NOT form ____ with HNO2.</text>
            <option id="A">Stable nitroso compounds or alcohols (form soluble salts)</option><option id="B">Salt</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They form nitrite salts (R3NH+ NO2-).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Anisidine is an amine with ____ group.</text>
            <option id="A">-OCH3 and -NH2</option><option id="B">-CH3 and -NH2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Methoxy-substituted aniline (o, m, p isomers).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity of anilinium ion: It is ____ than ammonium ion.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher (NH2 is less basic than NH3)</option><option id="B">Lower</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher Ka for conjugate acid means weaker base.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Effect of EDG on aniline basicity? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases basic strength</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: p-Toluidine is more basic than aniline.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Effect of EWG on aniline basicity? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases basic strength</option><option id="B">Increases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: p-Nitroaniline is less basic than aniline.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Azo dyes contain ____ linkage.</text>
            <option id="A">-N=N-</option><option id="B">-NH-CO-</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extended conjugation leads to color.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Zwitterion form of sulphanilic acid exists because of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amphoteric nature (Acidic -SO3H and Basic -NH2)</option><option id="B">Presence of S</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Internal proton transfer.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aniline reacting with cold NaNO2 + H2SO4 at 273-278 K yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzenediazonium hydrogen sulphate</option><option id="B">Nitrobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard diazotization.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction [ArN2]+ X- + H2O (warm) -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenol (ArOH)</option><option id="B">Benzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aqueous decomposition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction [ArN2]+ X- + H3PO2 + H2O -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzene (ArH)</option><option id="B">Phenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Deamination (reduction).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Benzaldehyde reacting with Aniline yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzylidene aniline (Schiff's base)</option><option id="B">Benzamide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anhydro-reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitration of aniline with nitrating mixture gives ____ of p, m, o isomers.</text>
            <option id="A">51%, 47%, 2%</option><option id="B">100% para</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Significant meta product is unusual but explained by acidity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bromination of protected aniline (Acetanilide) followed by hydrolysis gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-bromoaniline (majorly)</option><option id="B">o/p mixture</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acetamido group is less activating and bulkier than -NH2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of Nitrobenzene with Sn/HCl gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aniline</option><option id="B">Azobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common acidic reduction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of methyl isocyanide (CH3NC) on hydrolysis?</text>
            <option id="A">Gives Methylamine and Formic acid</option><option id="B">Gives Acetic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Yields primary amine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of isocyanides (RNC) with Sodium/Ethanol gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary amines (R-NH-CH3)</option><option id="B">Primary amines</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>N-methylamines.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkyl isocyanides are ____ poisonous than cyanides.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extremely toxic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hofmann's exhaustive methylation yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Quaternary ammonium salt</option><option id="B">Tertiary amine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reaction with excess CH3I.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hofmann elimination from quaternary hydroxide follows ____ rule.</text>
            <option id="A">Hofmann's (Less substituted alkene)</option><option id="B">Zaitsev's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Opposite of Zaitsev rule.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Schiff's base can be reduced to ____ amines.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary (2°)</option><option id="B">Primary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reductive amination component.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which gas is evolved during reaction of primary amines with HNO2?</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrogen (N2)</option><option id="B">Nitric oxide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Effervescence observed.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of aniline in water is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Very low (Insoluble)</option><option id="B">High</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Larger hydrophobic phenyl group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aniline is stored in dark bottles because it ____ on exposure to air/light.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidizes to form colored products</option><option id="B">Evaporates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Turns brown/black.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of aniline with CH3I (excess) yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenyltrimethylammonium iodide</option><option id="B">Methylaniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exhaustive methylation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Separation of amines mixture using Fractional Distillation is possible if ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Boiling points are sufficiently different</option><option id="B">Always</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on physical properties.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Preparation of amines from Nitroalkanes using Sn/HCl is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Reduction</option><option id="B">Substitution</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard lab method.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of azides (RN3) gives ____ amines.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°)</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using LAH or H2/Pd.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mechanism for Gabriel Phthalimide synthesis involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">SN2 attack of phthalimide ion on RX</option><option id="B">Addition</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Limited to primary halides.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is the strongest base in aqueous solution?</text>
            <option id="A">Diethylamine [(C2H5)2NH]</option><option id="B">Triethylamine</option><option id="C">Ethylamine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secondary ethyl amine is most basic due to balanced effects.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is the strongest base in aqueous solution?</text>
            <option id="A">Dimethylamine [(CH3)2NH]</option><option id="B">Trimethylamine</option><option id="C">Methylamine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secondary methyl amine is most basic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basicity order: p-toluidine vs aniline vs p-nitroaniline? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-toluidine &gt; aniline &gt; p-nitroaniline</option><option id="B">aniline &gt; p-toluidine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>EDG increases basicity, EWG decreases it.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which amine does NOT react with Hinsberg's reagent to give a precipitate?</text>
            <option id="A">Tertiary amine</option><option id="B">Secondary</option><option id="C">Primary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lacks H atom on Nitrogen to start the reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Action of Br2/NaOH on Propanamide gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ethanamine</option><option id="B">Propanamine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hoffmann degradation removes carbonyl carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mechanism for Hoffmann Bromamide degradation involves ____ intermediate.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkyl isocyanate (R-N=C=O)</option><option id="B">Carbocation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rearrangement of nitrene-like species.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aniline to Benzoic acid conversion involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diazotization -&gt; Sandmeyer (CuCN) -&gt; Hydrolysis</option><option id="B">Friedel-Crafts</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common multi-step synthesis path.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coupling of diazonium salt with beta-naphthol gives ____ dye.</text>
            <option id="A">Scarlet / Red</option><option id="B">Yellow</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used as a characteristic test for primary aromatic amines.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of benzenediazonium chloride with SnCl2/HCl yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenylhydrazine</option><option id="B">Aniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Useful reagent for sugar analysis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction [ArN2]+ Cl- + CuCN/KCN -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzonitrile (ArCN)</option><option id="B">Aniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Replacement by -CN group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gomberg-Bachmann reaction: ArN2+ + Benzene (in base) -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Biphenyl</option><option id="B">Aniline</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Coupling to form biaryls.</explanation></question>
        <question>
